# Website - Intro

This series of blog posts will dive deep into this website (incl. the blog).
Used technologies and design decisions will be explained.
This is the introduction post of this series.

## Overview

First of all, let's get an overview of this website.  
There are multiple components that are required to run this website:  

- **Frontend:**  
This is the part you can actually see.  
It consists out of the [main-page] and the [blog].  
Blog-Post going in detail about the **frontend** can be found [here](https://sakul6499.de/blog/2)

- **Backend:**  
The **frontend** (mainly the [blog]-part) requires data to function completely.  
Each blog post must be stored somewhere and the **frontend** must access the stored data somehow.  
This is what the **backend** is for.
It connects the **frontend** with the **data-layer**.  
Blog-Post going in detail about the **backend** can be found [here](https://sakul6499.de/blog/3)

- **Data-Layer:**  
Storing data persistently is actually harder to do than it sounds.  
Previously, one of the first versions of my website, used a simple hosted JSON 'mater file' which defined at which path a markdown file lies.  
This, however, is inefficient and tasks like searching or sorting is done by and on the client (e.g. bad on mobile).  
The current website uses a [nosql] database [mongodb].  
Blog-Post going in detail about the **data-layer** can be found [here](https://sakul6499.de/blog/4)

- **Orchestration & Deployment:**  
While not being a direct part of the application, this part ties everything together and makes sure deployment is as easy as possible.
Currently, this is done with [docker].  
This step also includes building the different projects and capsulating them into container (micro-services).
The entire source code and deployment is managed, performed and hosted by [gitlab-repo].  
Blog-Post going in detail about the frontend can be found [here](https://sakul6499.de/blog/2)
